    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yo i was doing some sprints today and my legs felt like they were on fire lol. can u explain what actually happens with the lactic acid when u push that hard? like how does it get made and how does it go away?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When you sprint hard, your muscles switch to anaerobic energy production due to the demand for quick energy. To provide this energy in the absence of oxygen, your body initially uses glucose. However, when your muscles are straining for extended periods, glucose levels may become depleted, prompting the breakdown of pyruvate, which is typically converted to less toxic lactate during oxygen-rich conditions. During intense exercise, pyruvate is converted to lactate, which can help delay muscle fatigue and continue energy production. Lactic acid buildup leads to the familiar burning sensation. Once you slow down, your body can reoxidize lactate, making use of it for energy, or transport it to the liver where it will be converted back into glucose through a process called gluconeogenesis. Rest allows your body to recover, lactate levels to drop, reducing the burning sensation and enabling you to perform comfortably again.",
      "source": "target",
