    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so it's like a byproduct that helps you keep going but then causes the burn? that's kinda weird. is there like a specific point where it just becomes too much for the muscles to handle? like a threshold or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, your legs \"burning\" sensation is indeed a byproduct of lactic acid being generated as a fuel source during intense physical exertion. When exercising above a certain intensity, typically above the lactate threshold, your body starts to produce lactic acid faster than it can be cleared out (aerobically or converted back to glucose). There isn't just one \"muscle threshold,\" but there is a concept known as the lactate threshold, which is an individual-specific marker that denotes the exercise intensity at which lactate begins to accumulate in the bloodstream. For many people, the lactate threshold occurs at around 50-75% of their maximal aerobic capacity. Past this limit, the muscles produce an abundance of lactate that cannot be utilized immediately, thus leading to that burning feeling in your legs. Your body can only handle a certain amount before fatigue sets in, decreasing your ability to sustain peak force production or power output for your sprinting duration.",
      "source": "target",
